{{Orphan|date=May 2011}}
'''Expenditure incidence''' is the effect of [[government expenditure]] upon the distribution of private incomes.  This is commonly contrasted with [[benefit incidence]] as an approach to planning and measuring the effect of a government spending programme.  A pioneering analysis of this was made  by the economist [[Richard Musgrave (economist)|Richard Musgrave]] in his major work, ''The Theory of Public Finance''.<ref>{{citation |title=Economy planning and policies |author=K.N.Reddy |chapter=Incidence of Public Expenditure in Andhra Pradhesh |isbn=978-81-7022-320-7 |year=1990 |pages=51–74}}</ref>

Establishing the differential effect of expenditure in this way is difficult because the effect of differing policies upon taxation and overall expenditure must be normalised and it is hard to model and measure the flows of money which result.<ref>{{citation |title=Public Finance |author=David N. Hyman |chapter=Taxation, Prices, Efficiency, and the Distribution of Income |year=2010 |isbn=978-0-538-75446-0 |pages=445–488}}</ref>

An analysis will commonly be structured in three stages:<ref>{{citation |title=Public expenditure analysis |chapter=Public Expenditure Incidence Analysis |author=Giuseppe Ruggeri |isbn=978-0-8213-6144-3 |year=2005 |pages=1–32}}</ref>

#Definition of the government programmes or budgetary expenditures and the corresponding database of monetary values.
#Determining the measures of income: the size of economic unit such as the individual, family or community; the timescale of analysis such as annual or lifetime; the well-being and externalities which arise from the expenditure.
#The resulting effects upon income distribution as a result of the expenditure are then calculated.  These will typically be presented graphically as a [[Lorenz curve]] or in the form of an index such as the [[Gini coefficient]].

